Yes you are right.
In my case I was trying to augment from submodule_a a container defined in a grouping in submodule_b which grouping is then used by the main module. Rereading the augment statement definition in RFC6020 I think this is not allowed, because basically it is an augment from a submodule to its main module.

Modified the example above:
$ cat x-base.yang
module x-base {
    yang-version 1;
    namespace "http://example.com/x-base";
    prefix x-b;
    include x-base2;
    include x-profiles;
    container x-setting {
        uses x-base2-setting;
    }
}
$ cat x-base2.yang 
submodule x-base2 {
    yang-version 1;
    belongs-to x-base {
        prefix x-b;
    }
    grouping x-base2-setting {
        container configs {
            container profiles {
            }
        }
    }
}
$ cat x-profiles.yang 
submodule x-profiles {
    yang-version 1;
    belongs-to x-base {
        prefix x-b;
    }
    include x-base2;
    augment "/x-b:x-setting/x-b:configs/x-b:profiles" {
        list profile {
            key name;
            leaf name {
                type string;
            }
        }
    }
}
$ pyang x-base.yang
x-profiles.yang:7: error: node x-base::x-setting is not found

Could you confirm if my interpretation is correct?

@paulfitz -- sorry for the long silence. I've been caught in other things and this became much less important. In fact, I'm still busy with other things and I don't have time to work further on this, but let me share my thoughts.

I think the `n` and `m` way should work, but would be too complicated for the casual user, whereas a single precision parameter is easier to understand. The question is who is your "average" user? 

Alternatively, we can let the floating point diff work only for my use case (fixed number of rows and columns) which should be straightforward, and then see what other people think of it (and maybe someone else would make a PR extending the functionality).

